## Launching the Error

To manually trigger a crash and alert the system of a violation, use the `throw` keyword followed by an Exception object.

```dart
void withdraw(int amount) {
  if (amount < 0) {
    // Crash the program right here!
    throw Exception('Amount cannot be negative!');
  }

  print('Withdrawing $amount');
}
```

## Making it Meaningful

The generic `Exception` is fine, but Dart has highly specific ones like `ArgumentError` (when a parameter is invalid) or `StateError`.

```dart
void login(String username) {
  if (username.isEmpty) {
    throw ArgumentError('Username cannot be totally empty!');
  }
}
```
This tells the developer EXACTLY what kind of mistake they made!

